WEBVTT

00:05.280 --> 00:11.960
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus

00:11.960 --> 00:13.860
Translated by George Long

00:14.420 --> 00:18.720
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:19.280 --> 00:23.300
For more information or to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:24.360 --> 00:25.480
Section 10.

00:29.160 --> 00:33.100
Wilt thou then, my soul, never be good and simple, and one and naked,

00:33.600 --> 00:35.820
more manifest than the body which surrounds thee?

00:36.960 --> 00:39.740
Wilt thou never enjoy an affectionate and contented disposition?

00:40.640 --> 00:43.660
Wilt thou never be full and without a want of any kind,

00:43.720 --> 00:47.780
longing for nothing more, nor desiring anything, either animate or inanimate,

00:48.060 --> 00:49.460
for the enjoyment of pleasures?

00:50.100 --> 00:54.160
Nor yet desiring time wherein thou shalt have longer enjoyment, or place,

00:54.560 --> 00:58.020
or pleasant climate, or society of men with whom thou mayest live in harmony?

00:59.000 --> 01:01.700
But wilt thou be satisfied with thy present condition,

01:02.180 --> 01:04.100
and pleased with all that is about thee?

01:04.260 --> 01:07.580
And wilt thou convince thyself that thou hast everything,

01:07.580 --> 01:10.900
and that it comes from the gods, that everything is well for thee,

01:11.000 --> 01:12.960
and will be well whatever shall please them,

01:13.420 --> 01:16.760
and whatever they shall give for the conservation of perfect living being,

01:17.080 --> 01:21.560
the good, and just, and beautiful, which generates and holds together all things,

01:22.060 --> 01:24.560
and contains and embraces all things which are dissolved

01:24.560 --> 01:26.500
for the production of other like things?

01:27.760 --> 01:31.760
Wilt thou never be such that thou shalt so dwell in community with gods and men,

01:31.880 --> 01:35.660
as neither to find fault with them at all, nor to be condemned by them?

01:36.760 --> 01:44.620
2. Observe what thy nature requires, so far as thou art governed by nature only.

01:44.900 --> 01:46.740
Then do it, and accept it.

01:47.060 --> 01:51.160
If thy nature, so far as thou art a living being, shall not be made worse by it.

01:52.160 --> 01:55.200
And next thou must observe what thy nature requires,

01:55.420 --> 01:56.940
so far as thou art a living being.

01:57.860 --> 02:01.000
And all this thou mayest allow thyself, if thy nature,

02:01.220 --> 02:04.960
so far as thou art a rational animal, shall not be made worse by it.

02:05.660 --> 02:09.280
But the rational animal is consequently also a political animal.

02:10.420 --> 02:14.000
Use these rules then, and trouble thyself about nothing else.

02:16.920 --> 02:22.280
3. Everything which happens, either happens in such wise

02:22.280 --> 02:27.660
as thou art formed by nature to bear it, or as thou art not formed by nature to bear it.

02:28.560 --> 02:32.240
If then it happens to thee in such a way as thou art formed by nature to bear it,

02:32.240 --> 02:36.200
do not complain, but bear it as thou art formed by nature to bear it.

02:37.120 --> 02:40.940
But if it happens in such wise as thou art not formed by nature to bear it,

02:41.140 --> 02:44.900
do not complain, for it will perish after it has consumed thee.

02:45.640 --> 02:49.080
Remember, however, that thou art formed by nature to bear everything,

02:49.520 --> 02:52.140
with respect to which it depends on thy own opinion to make it

02:52.140 --> 02:57.440
endurable and tolerable, by thinking that it is either thy interest or thy duty to do this.

02:58.300 --> 03:03.700
4. If a man is mistaken, instruct him kindly and show him his error.

03:04.300 --> 03:08.640
But if thou art not able, blame thyself, or blame not even thyself.

03:12.160 --> 03:17.900
5. Whatever may happen to thee, it was prepared for thee from all eternity,

03:18.400 --> 03:22.760
and the implication of causes was from eternity spinning the thread of thy being,

03:22.920 --> 03:24.900
and of that which is incident to it.

03:26.660 --> 03:34.400
6. Whether the universe is a concourse of atoms, or nature as a system, let this first be established,

03:34.780 --> 03:37.740
that I am part of the whole which is governed by nature, next,

03:38.100 --> 03:42.600
I am in a manner intimately related to the parts which are of the same kind with myself.

03:43.800 --> 03:46.320
For remembering this, inasmuch as I am a part,

03:46.700 --> 03:50.500
I shall be discontented with none of the things which are assigned to me out of the whole.

03:51.140 --> 03:55.560
For nothing is injurious to the part if it is for the advantage of the whole.

03:56.580 --> 03:59.220
For the whole contains nothing which is not for its advantage,

03:59.840 --> 04:03.920
and all natures indeed have this common principle, but the nature of the universe

04:03.920 --> 04:08.780
has this principle besides that it cannot be compelled even by any external cause

04:08.780 --> 04:10.900
to generate anything harmful to itself.

04:12.460 --> 04:16.720
By remembering, then, that I am part of such a whole, I shall be content with everything that

04:16.720 --> 04:21.260
happens, and inasmuch as I am in a manner intimately related to the parts which are

04:21.260 --> 04:26.880
of the same kind with myself, I shall do nothing unsocial, but I shall rather direct myself to the

04:26.880 --> 04:31.980
things which are of the same kind with myself, and I shall turn all my efforts to the common interest,

04:32.340 --> 04:33.960
and divert them from the contrary.

04:35.380 --> 04:38.860
Now, if these things are done so, life must flow on happily,

04:39.040 --> 04:42.060
just as thou mayest observe that the life of a citizen is happy,

04:42.440 --> 04:46.240
who continues a course of action which is advantageous to his fellow citizens,

04:46.240 --> 04:49.440
and is content with whatever the state may assign to him.

04:53.700 --> 05:00.340
7. The parts of the whole, everything I mean, which is naturally comprehended in the universe,

05:00.860 --> 05:06.900
must of necessity perish. But let this be understood in this sense, that they must undergo

05:06.900 --> 05:13.500
change. But if this is naturally both an evil and a necessity for the parts, the whole would not

05:13.500 --> 05:18.220
continue to exist in a good condition, the parts being subject to change and constituted so as to

05:18.220 --> 05:24.260
perish in various ways. For whether did Nature herself design to do evil to the things which

05:24.260 --> 05:29.460
are parts of herself, and to make them subject to evil and of necessity fall into evil,

05:29.820 --> 05:36.180
or have such results happened without her knowing it? Both these suppositions indeed are incredible,

05:36.740 --> 05:41.900
but if a man should ever drop the term Nature as an efficient power, and should speak of these

05:41.900 --> 05:47.280
as natural, even then it would be ridiculous to affirm at the same time that the parts of the

05:47.280 --> 05:52.160
whole are in their nature subject to change, and at the same time to be surprised or vexed as if

05:52.160 --> 05:57.140
something were happening contrary to Nature, particularly as the dissolution of things into

05:57.140 --> 06:03.060
those things of which each thing is composed. For there is either a dispersion of the elements out

06:03.060 --> 06:08.400
of which everything has been compounded, or a change from the solid to the earthy, and from the

06:08.400 --> 06:13.500
aerial, so that these parts are taken back into the universal reason, whether this at certain

06:13.500 --> 06:20.640
periods is consumed by fire or renewed by eternal changes. And do not imagine that the solid and the

06:20.640 --> 06:26.360
airy part belong to thee from time of generation. For all this received its accretion only yesterday,

06:26.900 --> 06:32.780
and the day before, as one may say, from the food and the air which is inspired. This then,

06:32.860 --> 06:36.820
which have received the accretion, changes not that which thy mother brought forth.

06:37.460 --> 06:41.900
But suppose that this, which thy mother brought forth, implicates thee very much with the other

06:41.900 --> 06:47.320
part, which has the peculiar quality of change. This is nothing, in fact, in the way of objection

06:47.320 --> 06:57.260
to what is said. 8. When thou hast assumed thy names, good, modest, true, rational, a man of

06:57.260 --> 07:02.960
equanimity and magnanimous, take care thou dost not change these names. And if thou should lose

07:02.960 --> 07:08.900
them, quickly return to them. And remember that the term rational was intended to signify a

07:08.900 --> 07:14.600
discriminating attention to every several thing and freedom from negligence, and that equanimity

07:14.600 --> 07:18.600
is the voluntary acceptance of the things which are assigned to thee by the common nature,

07:19.240 --> 07:23.620
and that magnanimity is the elevation of the intelligent part above the pleasurable or

07:23.620 --> 07:29.300
painful sensations of the flesh, and above that poor thing called fame, and death, and all such

07:29.300 --> 07:35.980
things. 9. If then thou maintainest thyself in the possession of these names, without desiring

07:35.980 --> 07:41.380
to be called by these names by others, thou wilt be another person and wilt enter on to another

07:41.380 --> 07:48.380
life. For to continue to be such as thou hast hitherto been, and to be torn in pieces and defiled

07:48.380 --> 07:55.000
in such a life, is the character of a very stupid man, and one over-fond of his life. And like those

07:55.000 --> 07:59.080
half-devoured fighters with wild beasts, who though covered with wounds and gore, are still

07:59.080 --> 08:03.680
entreat to be kept to the following day, though they will be exposed in the same state to the

08:03.680 --> 08:10.280
same claws and bites. Therefore, fix thyself in the possession of these few names, and if

08:10.280 --> 08:15.500
thou art able to abide in them, abide as if thou wast removed to certain islands of the happy.

08:17.080 --> 08:21.540
But if thou shalt perceive that thou fallest out of them and dost not maintain thy hold,

08:21.540 --> 08:27.520
go courageously into some nook where thou shalt maintain them, or even depart at once from life,

08:27.800 --> 08:33.420
not in passion, but with simplicity and freedom and modesty, after doing this one laudable thing

08:33.420 --> 08:39.960
at least in thy life, to have gone out of it thus. In order, however, to the remembrance

08:39.960 --> 08:45.100
of these names, it will greatly help thee if thou rememberest the gods, and that they wish

08:45.100 --> 08:50.440
not to be flattered, but wish all reasonable beings to be made like themselves. And if

08:50.440 --> 08:55.480
thou rememberest, that which does the work of a fig tree is a fig tree, and that which does the

08:55.480 --> 09:01.880
work of a dog is a dog, and that which does the work of a bee is a bee, and that which does the

09:01.880 --> 09:10.860
work of man is a man. 9. Meme, war, astonishment, torpor,

09:10.920 --> 09:17.000
slavery, will daily wipe out those holy principles of thine. How many things without studying nature

09:17.000 --> 09:23.680
dost thou imagine, and how many dost thou neglect? But it is thy duty so to look on,

09:23.760 --> 09:28.800
and so to do everything, that at the same time the power of dealing with circumstances is perfect,

09:29.140 --> 09:34.000
and the contemplative faculty is exercised, and the confidence which comes from the knowledge of

09:34.000 --> 09:42.100
each several thing is maintained without showing it, by yet not concealed. For when wilt thou enjoy

09:42.100 --> 09:48.060
simplicity, when gravity, and when the knowledge of every several thing, both what is in substance,

09:48.340 --> 09:52.760
and what place it has in the universe, and how long it is formed to exist, and of what things

09:52.760 --> 09:58.600
it is compounded, and to whom it can belong, and who are able both to give it and take it away?

10:02.040 --> 10:09.220
10. A spider is proud when it has caught a fly, and another when he has caught a poor hair,

10:09.780 --> 10:15.440
and another when he has taken the little fish in the net, and another when he has taken wild boars,

10:16.000 --> 10:20.480
and another when he has taken bears, and another when he has taken sarmatians.

10:21.620 --> 10:24.600
Are not these robbers, if thou examinest their opinions?

10:26.940 --> 10:32.980
11. Acquire the contemplative way of seeing how all things change into one another,

10:33.380 --> 10:38.180
and constantly attend to it, and exercise thyself about this part of philosophy.

10:39.220 --> 10:44.820
For nothing is so much adapted produce magnanimity. Such a man is put off the body,

10:45.360 --> 10:51.360
and he sees that he must, no one knows how soon, go away from among men and leave everything here.

10:51.760 --> 10:56.980
He gives himself up entirely to just doing in all his actions, and in everything else that happens,

10:57.120 --> 11:03.620
he resigns himself to the universal nature. But as to what any man shall say or think about him,

11:03.660 --> 11:09.000
or do against him, he never even thinks of it, being himself contented with these two things.

11:09.220 --> 11:15.080
With acting justly in what he now does, and being satisfied with what is now assigned to him.

11:16.080 --> 11:20.720
And he lays aside all distracting and busy pursuits, and desires nothing else

11:20.720 --> 11:25.260
than to accomplish the straight course through the law, and by accomplishing the straight course,

11:25.420 --> 11:29.200
to follow God. 12.

11:31.180 --> 11:36.100
What need is there of suspicious fear, since it is thy power to inquire what ought to be done?

11:36.620 --> 11:41.300
And if thou seest clear, go by this way content, without turning back.

11:41.820 --> 11:45.680
But if thou dost not see clear, stop and take the best advisers.

11:46.960 --> 11:51.840
But if any other things oppose thee, go on according to thy powers with due consideration,

11:52.020 --> 11:56.680
keeping to that which appears to be just. For it is best to reach this object,

11:56.740 --> 12:02.580
and if thou dost fail, let thy failure be in attempting this. He who follows reason in all

12:02.580 --> 12:07.860
things is both tranquil and active at the same time, and also cheerful and collected.

12:11.580 --> 12:12.080
13.

12:14.420 --> 12:18.940
Inquire of thyself, as soon as thou wakest from sleep, whether it will make any difference to thee,

12:19.080 --> 12:25.560
if another does what is just and right. It will make no difference. Thou hast not forgotten,

12:25.600 --> 12:29.940
I suppose, that those who assume arrogant errors in bestowing their praise or blame on others,

12:29.940 --> 12:35.140
are such as they are at bed and at board. And thou hast not forgotten what they do,

12:35.480 --> 12:39.140
and what they avoid, and what they pursue, and how they steal, and how they rob,

12:39.420 --> 12:44.600
not with hands and feet, but with their most valuable part, by means of which there is produced

12:44.600 --> 12:50.360
when a man chooses fidelity, modesty, truth, law, a good demon, and happiness.

12:52.060 --> 12:52.540
14.

12:54.260 --> 12:59.960
To her who gives and takes back all, to nature, the man who is instructed in modest says,

13:00.380 --> 13:05.240
Give what thy wilt, take back what thou wilt. And he says this not proudly,

13:05.540 --> 13:07.540
but obediently, and well pleased with her.

13:10.260 --> 13:10.780
15.

13:12.580 --> 13:18.400
Short is the little which remains to thee of life. Live as on a mountain. For it makes no

13:18.400 --> 13:22.980
difference whether a man lives there or here, if he lives everywhere in the world as an estate.

13:24.260 --> 13:27.960
Let men see, let them know a real man who lives according to nature.

13:28.800 --> 13:34.100
If they cannot endure him, let them kill him. For that is better than to live like this.

13:37.040 --> 13:37.520
16.

13:39.160 --> 13:44.160
No longer talk at all about the kind of man that a good man ought to be, but be such.

13:46.220 --> 13:46.700
17.

13:48.300 --> 13:52.800
Constantly contemplate the whole of time and the whole of substance, and consider that all

13:52.800 --> 13:58.700
individual things as to substance are as a grain of a fig, and as to time the turning of a gimlet.

14:03.360 --> 14:08.140
Look at everything that exists, and observe that it is already in dissolution and in change,

14:08.760 --> 14:14.380
and as it were putrefaction or dispersion, or that everything is so constituted by nature as to die.

14:16.200 --> 14:16.680
19.

14:18.620 --> 14:22.660
Consider what men are when they are eating, sleeping, generating, easing themselves,

14:22.740 --> 14:27.140
and so forth. Then what kind of men they are when they are imperious and arrogant,

14:27.420 --> 14:33.840
or angry and scolding from their elevated place. Put a short time ago to how many they were slaves

14:33.840 --> 14:38.780
and for what things. And after a little time, consider in what a condition they will be.

14:41.080 --> 14:41.560
20.

14:43.240 --> 14:47.340
That is for the good of each thing which the universal nature brings to each,

14:47.780 --> 14:50.740
and it is for its good at the time when nature brings it.

14:53.000 --> 14:53.520
21.

14:54.960 --> 15:02.440
The earth loves a shower, and the solemn aether loves, and the universe loves to make whatever

15:02.440 --> 15:09.460
it is about to be. I say then to the universe that I love as thou lovest, and is not this too said

15:09.460 --> 15:12.540
this or that loves as want to be produced.

15:14.540 --> 15:15.100
22.

15:17.520 --> 15:21.460
Either thou livest here, and hast already accustomed thyself to it,

15:21.640 --> 15:28.120
or thou art going away, and this was on thy own will, or thou art dying, and hast discharged thy

15:28.120 --> 15:32.940
duty. But besides these things there is nothing. Be of good cheer then.

15:35.520 --> 15:36.080
23.

15:37.860 --> 15:42.460
Let this always be plain to thee, that this piece of land is like any other,

15:42.640 --> 15:45.860
and that all things here are the same with things on top of a mountain,

15:46.060 --> 15:52.040
or on the seashore, or wherever thou choosest to be. For thou wilt find just what Plato says,

15:52.520 --> 15:55.980
dwelling within the walls of a city as in a shepherd's fold on a mountain.

15:58.720 --> 15:59.160
24.

16:00.440 --> 16:05.680
What is my ruling faculty now to me? And of what nature am I now making it?

16:05.680 --> 16:11.620
And for what purpose am I now using it? Is it void of understanding? Is it loosed and rent

16:11.620 --> 16:16.580
asunder from social life? Is it melted into and mixed with the poor flesh so as to move together

16:16.580 --> 16:20.560
with it? 25.

16:22.020 --> 16:27.660
He who flies from his master is a runaway, but the law is master, and he who breaks the law

16:27.660 --> 16:34.120
is a runaway. And he also who is grieved or angry or afraid is dissatisfied because something has

16:34.120 --> 16:38.880
been or is or shall be of the things which are appointed by him who rules all things,

16:39.200 --> 16:46.260
and he is law and assigns to every man what is fit. He then who fears or is grieved or is angry

16:46.260 --> 16:50.220
is a runaway. 26.

16:52.740 --> 16:58.460
A man deposits seed in a womb and goes away, and then another cause takes it and labors on it and

16:58.460 --> 17:06.100
makes a child. What a thing from such a material! Again, the child passes food down the throat,

17:06.560 --> 17:11.120
and then another cause takes it and makes it perception and motion. And in fine life and

17:11.120 --> 17:16.540
strength and other things, how many and how strange! Observe, then, the things which are

17:16.540 --> 17:21.280
produced in such a hidden way, and see the power just as we see the power which carries

17:21.280 --> 17:26.180
things downwards and upwards, not with the eyes, but still no less plainly.

17:29.180 --> 17:29.700
27.

17:31.420 --> 17:35.920
Constantly consider how all things such as they now are and time past also were,

17:36.180 --> 17:40.980
and consider that they will be the same again. And place before thy eyes entire dramas and

17:40.980 --> 17:45.780
stages of the same form, whatever thou hast learned from thy experience or from older history.

17:46.360 --> 17:52.280
For example, the whole court of Hadrianus, and the whole court of Antoninus, and the whole court of

17:52.280 --> 17:58.700
Olympus, Alexander, Croesus, for all those were dramas such as we see now only with different actors.

18:00.400 --> 18:05.660
28. Imagine every man who is grieved at anything or discontented to be like a pig

18:05.660 --> 18:12.420
which is sacrificed in kicks and screams. Like this pig also is he who on his bed in silence

18:12.420 --> 18:17.080
laments the bonds in which we are held, and consider that only to the rational animal is

18:17.080 --> 18:23.080
given to follow voluntarily what happens, but simply to follow as a necessity imposed on all.

18:25.440 --> 18:26.000
29.

18:27.580 --> 18:32.320
Severally on the occasion of everything that thou dost, pause and ask thyself if death is

18:32.320 --> 18:40.460
a dreadful thing because it deprives thee of this. 30. When thou art offended at any man's fault,

18:41.000 --> 18:44.980
forwith turn to thyself and reflect in what like manner thou dost err thyself,

18:44.980 --> 18:49.780
for example in thinking that money is a good thing, or pleasure, or a bit of reputation,

18:49.920 --> 18:55.220
and the like. For by attending to this thou wilt quickly forget thy anger, if this consideration

18:55.220 --> 19:01.420
also is added, that the man is compelled for what else could he do. Or, if thou art able,

19:01.680 --> 19:09.960
take away from him the compulsion. 31. When thou hast seen Sartron the Socratic,

19:09.960 --> 19:16.600
think of Eutyches or Hymen. And when thou hast seen Euphrates, think of Eutychion or Silvanus.

19:17.660 --> 19:23.260
And when thou hast seen Alcefron, think of Troipaphorus. And when thou hast seen Xenophon,

19:23.520 --> 19:29.300
think of Credo of Severus. And when thou hast looked on thyself, think of any other Caesar,

19:30.060 --> 19:34.820
and in the case of every one do in like manner. 32.

19:34.820 --> 19:39.340
Then let this thought be in thy mind. Where then are those men?

19:39.980 --> 19:46.580
Nowhere, or nobody knows where. For thus continuously thou wilt look at human things

19:46.580 --> 19:51.740
as smoke and nothing at all, especially if thou reflectest at the same time that what

19:51.740 --> 19:58.260
has once changed will never exist again in the infinite duration of time. But thou,

19:58.720 --> 20:04.320
in what a brief space of time is thy existence, and why art thou not content to pass through

20:04.320 --> 20:10.160
this short time in an orderly way? What matter and opportunity for thy activity art thou avoiding?

20:10.800 --> 20:14.260
For what else are all these things except exercises for the reason,

20:14.540 --> 20:19.460
when it is viewed carefully, and by examination into their nature the things which happen in life?

20:21.600 --> 20:26.880
Persevere then until thou shalt have made these things thy own, as the stomach which is strengthened

20:26.880 --> 20:32.300
makes all things its own, as the blazing fire makes flame and brightness out of everything that is

20:32.300 --> 20:40.300
thrown into it. 32.

20:42.140 --> 20:47.100
Let it not be in any man's power to say truly of thee that thou art not simple, or that thou art

20:47.100 --> 20:52.700
not good. But let him be a liar whoever shall think anything of this kind about thee, and this

20:52.700 --> 20:58.840
is altogether in thy power. For who is he that shall hinder thee from being good and simple?

20:59.480 --> 21:04.220
Do thou only determine to live no longer, and lest thou shalt be such?

21:05.360 --> 21:08.940
For neither does reason allow thee to live, if thou art not such.

21:11.620 --> 21:19.380
33. What is that which as to this material our life can be done or said in a way most

21:19.380 --> 21:25.280
conformable to reason? For whatever this may be, it is in thy power to do it or say it,

21:25.280 --> 21:31.160
and do not make excuses that thou art hindered. Thou wilt not cease to lament till thy mind is

21:31.160 --> 21:36.480
in such a condition that, what luxury is to those who enjoy pleasure, such shall be to thee

21:36.480 --> 21:41.200
in the matter which is subjected and presented to thee, the doing of things which are conformable

21:41.200 --> 21:46.940
to man's constitution. For a man ought to consider as an enjoyment everything which is in his power

21:46.940 --> 21:59.100
to do according to his own nature, and it is in his power everywhere. Now it is not given to a

21:59.100 --> 22:05.500
cylinder to move everywhere by its own motion, nor yet water, nor to fire, nor to anything else

22:05.500 --> 22:10.600
which is governed by nature of an irrational soul, for the things which check them and stand in the

22:10.600 --> 22:16.300
way are many. But intelligence and reason are able to go through everything that opposes them,

22:16.300 --> 22:22.560
and in such manner as they are formed by nature and as they choose. Place before thy eyes this

22:22.560 --> 22:28.080
facility with which the reason will be carried through all things, as fire upwards, as a stone

22:28.080 --> 22:35.980
downwards, as a cylinder down an inclined surface, and seek nothing further. For all other obstacles

22:35.980 --> 22:41.820
either affect the body only which is a dead thing, or except through opinion and the yielding of the

22:41.820 --> 22:48.620
they do not crush nor do any harm of any kind, for if they did, he who felt it would immediately

22:48.620 --> 22:55.920
become bad. Now in the case of all things which have a certain constitution, whatever harm may

22:55.920 --> 23:03.320
happen to any of them, that which is so affected becomes consequently worse. But in the like case,

23:03.420 --> 23:08.980
a man becomes both better if one may say so, and more worthy of praise by making a right use of

23:08.980 --> 23:16.420
accidents. And finally, remember that nothing harms him who is really a citizen, which does not

23:16.420 --> 23:22.340
harm the state, nor yet does anything harm the state which does not harm law, and of these things

23:22.340 --> 23:29.520
which are called misfortunes, not one harms law. What then does not harm law does not harm either

23:29.520 --> 23:30.540
citizen.

23:35.280 --> 23:40.340
To him who is penetrated by true principles, even the briefest precept is sufficient,

23:40.880 --> 23:46.720
and any common precept, to remind him that he should be free from grief and fair. For example,

23:48.980 --> 23:54.040
leaves, some the wind scatters on the ground, so is the race of men.

23:56.000 --> 24:01.420
Leaves also are thy children, and leaves too are they who cry out as if they were worthy of credit

24:01.420 --> 24:07.460
and bestow their praise, or on the contrary curse, or secretly blame and sneer, and leaves in like

24:07.460 --> 24:13.580
manner are those who shall receive and transmit a man's fame to aftertimes. For all such things as

24:13.580 --> 24:21.840
these, quote, are produced in the season of spring, end quote, as the poet says. But the wind casts

24:21.840 --> 24:27.980
them down, then the forest produces other leaves in their places. But a brief existence is common

24:27.980 --> 24:34.300
to all things, and yet thou avoidest and pursuest all things as if they would be eternal. A little

24:34.300 --> 24:40.240
time and thou shalt close thy eyes, and him who has attended thee to thy grave another soon will lament.

24:45.000 --> 24:45.440
35.

24:48.180 --> 24:53.600
The healthy eye ought to see all visible things, and not to say, I wish for green things. For this

24:53.600 --> 24:59.140
is the condition of a diseased eye. And the healthy hearing and smelling ought to be ready to perceive

24:59.140 --> 25:04.200
all that can be heard and smelled. And the healthy stomach ought to be with respect to all food,

25:04.240 --> 25:07.620
just as the meal with respect to all things which it is formed to grind.

25:08.820 --> 25:13.580
And accordingly, the healthy understanding ought to be prepared for everything which happens.

25:14.140 --> 25:18.980
But that which says, let my dear children live, and let all men praise whatever I may do,

25:19.780 --> 25:24.440
is an eye which seeks for green things, or teeth which seek for soft things.

25:28.520 --> 25:29.040
36.

25:31.960 --> 25:35.620
There is no man so fortunate that there shall not be by him when he is dying,

25:35.620 --> 25:38.060
some who were pleased with what is going to happen.

25:39.800 --> 25:45.180
Suppose that he was a good and wise man. Will there not be at last someone to say to himself,

25:46.000 --> 25:49.480
Let us at last breathe freely, being relieved from this schoolmaster?

25:50.700 --> 25:56.120
It is true that he was harsh to none of us, but I perceive that he tacitly condemns us.

25:57.100 --> 26:03.760
This is what is said of a good man. But in our own case, how many other things are there for which

26:03.760 --> 26:08.640
are many who wish to get rid of us? Thou wilt consider this then when thou art dying,

26:09.040 --> 26:12.160
and thou wilt depart more contentedly by reflecting thus.

26:13.600 --> 26:18.760
I am going away from such a life, in which even my associates, in behalf of whom I have

26:18.760 --> 26:24.800
striven so much, prayed and cared, themselves wished me to depart, hoping perchance to get

26:24.800 --> 26:30.860
some little advantage by it. Why, then, should a man cling to a longer stay here?

26:32.560 --> 26:36.720
Do not, however, for this reason go away less kindly disposed to them,

26:37.220 --> 26:40.500
but preserving thy own character, and friendly and benevolent and mild,

26:40.780 --> 26:45.940
and on the other hand not, as if thou wast torn away, but as a man who dies a quiet death.

26:47.700 --> 26:53.500
The poor soul is easily separated from the body. Such also aught thy departure from men to be,

26:53.980 --> 26:56.980
for nature united thee to them, and associated thee.

26:57.940 --> 26:59.980
But does she now dissolve the union?

27:01.720 --> 27:06.140
Well, I am separated as from kinsmen, not, however, dragged resisting,

27:06.700 --> 27:11.560
but without compulsion, for this too is one of the things according to nature.

27:18.040 --> 27:22.860
Accustom thyself as much as possible on the occasion of anything being done by any person

27:22.860 --> 27:27.660
to inquire with thyself, for what object is this man doing this?

27:28.780 --> 27:32.060
But begin with thyself, and examine thyself first.

27:37.560 --> 27:41.600
Remember that this which pulls the strings is the thing which is hidden within.

27:42.200 --> 27:48.000
This is the power of persuasion. This is life. This, if one may say so, is man.

27:49.100 --> 27:52.960
In contemplating thyself never include the vessel which surrounds thee,

27:53.400 --> 27:59.860
and these instruments were attached about it, for they are like to an axe differing only in this,

28:00.600 --> 28:07.000
that they grow to the body. For indeed there is no more use in these parts without the cause

28:07.000 --> 28:13.640
which moves and checks them than in the weaver's shuttle, and the writer's pen, and the driver's whip.

28:18.000 --> 28:19.680
Of section 10.

